      "content": "{\"claim\": \"The collapse was caused by a systemic failure of the elite-directed gift-exchange and diplomatic-marriage network that had previously stabilized inter-polity relations, triggering a cascade of legitimacy crises and elite infighting.\", \"mechanism\": \"Palatial elites depended on a constant flow of exotic prestige goods (copper, tin, ivory, glass, perfumed oils) acquired through reciprocal royal gift-exchange and diplomatic marriages. A disruption in the supply of these goods—triggered by a shock to a key node—undermined the ability of rulers to reward their warrior elites and perform their ritual roles. This led to a crisis of legitimacy, internal rebellions, and the defection of military retainers, causing the palaces to be abandoned or destroyed from within. The network's high connectivity ensured that the failure of one major palace cascaded rapidly to others, as trade routes became unsafe and diplomatic norms collapsed.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\", \"Ugarit\", \"Levantine city-states\"], \"excludes\": [\"Egypt\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Archaeological evidence shows a gradual, centuries-long decline in trade volumes and elite material culture across the region, rather than a rapid, synchronous collapse.\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"The destruction layers at major Mycenaean and Levantine sites are consistently attributed to foreign invaders (e.g., Sea Peoples) with no evidence of internal conflict or elite residence abandonment prior to destruction.\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"Egyptian records and archaeological evidence show that Egypt's elite gift-exchange network was completely independent and did not rely on the same trade routes or partners as the Hittite-Mycenaean-Ugarit network.\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This explains why Egypt survived: its more centralized, Nilotic redistributive economy was less dependent